{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0cfa18e2-ea7e-47d0-abcb-088ef9cbad6d","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 5. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) with the SDK.\n- For long-running collection, use `--duration` or `Ctrl+C` to stop.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is useful for a quick live view of CPU/GC metrics before committing to a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"547ab1f5-8af3-45ca-8eca-d603064e4e3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"1B87:FF35F:C2E590:DF4696:6A0280B4"},"id":"acd35563-94c2-465b-95e4-997ce85ddfc0","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:22:07.713Z","parentId":"2f0024cc-26c4-489b-bf62-e6aaf4d598d6"}
